<h2>Page-Wide Policy</h2>
<p>Set a default policy for the entire page using a <code>&lt;meta&gt;</code> tag. Individual elements can still override it with their own <code>referrerpolicy</code> attribute.</p>

<code-block language="html" label="Page-wide policy with overrides">{{ metaExample | escape }}</code-block>

<h3>Policy Resolution Order</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Per-element <code>referrerpolicy</code> attribute (highest priority)</li>
  <li><code>&lt;meta name="referrer"&gt;</code> page-wide policy</li>
  <li><code>Referrer-Policy</code> HTTP header</li>
  <li>Browser default (<code>strict-origin-when-cross-origin</code>)</li>
</ol>

<h2>Common Mistakes</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Lazy-loading every page to <code>no-referrer</code></strong> breaks analytics and affiliate attribution. Use a targeted approach instead.</li>
  <li><strong>Using <code>unsafe-url</code></strong> sends the full URL including query strings, even over HTTP. Avoid unless you have a specific need and trust the destination.</li>
  <li><strong>Forgetting protocol downgrade:</strong> Policies without "strict" in the name may still send referrers on HTTPS-to-HTTP requests. Prefer <code>strict-*</code> variants.</li>
</ul>

